          "body": "The prophet now addresses Zion in the third person, announcing what God will do on 'that day.' The oracle has three movements: boundary expansion (7:11), regathering of exiles from every direction (7:12), and the desolation of the earth that has harbored injustice (7:13). The wall-building of 7:11 is the reversal of conquest — the demolished walls of Jerusalem will be rebuilt and the boundary that defined the covenant inheritance will be extended beyond its former limits. The gathering of 7:12 is cosmic in scope: from Assyria (Israel's greatest oppressor in Micah's era) to Egypt (the ancient place of slavery), from sea to sea and mountain to mountain. This language will echo in Zechariah 9:10 and ultimately in the new creation vision of Revelation 21-22, where the same cosmological boundaries describe the full inheritance of God's people. Verse 13 is the dark counterpart: the same earth that will welcome the regathered people will become desolate for those whose deeds warranted it. The day of restoration and the day of final reckoning are the same day, viewed from different positions. As Calvin noted, God's mercy and God's judgment are not in tension; they are two faces of the same covenant faithfulness."
